<body>
    <h1>1_Basic Physics</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <p></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Basic elements: charge, Coulomb=E2=80=99s law, electric field, Gauss=E2=
=80=99s law, electric potential, magnetic field; Faraday=E2=80=99s law, Max=
well=E2=80=99s equations</p></li>
<li>
<p>Waves and oscillations</p></li>
<li>
<p>Theory of special relativity</p></li>
<li>
<p>Electromagnetic waves, Photoelectric effect, Quantum theory of light, X-=
ray and X-ray diffraction, Compton effect</p></li>
<li>
<p>De Broglie waves, Phase and group velocity, Wave function and wave equat=
ion.</p></li>
</ol>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Basic elements: charge, Coulomb=E2=80=99s law, electric field, Gauss=E2=
=80=99s law, electric potential, magnetic field; Faraday=E2=80=99s law, Max=
well=E2=80=99s equations</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Perfect =F0=9F=91=8F =E2=80=94 now let=E2=80=99s explain <strong>Basic E=
lements of Electromagnetism</strong>, which include <strong>charge, electri=
c &amp; magnetic fields, and Maxwell=E2=80=99s equations</strong> =E2=80=94=
 key concepts in <strong>electronics and physics for IT/Govt exams</strong>=
.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=E2=9A=A11.Charge">=E2=9A=A1 <strong>1. Charge<=
/strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Charge is a <strong>fundamental property of=
 matter</strong> that causes <strong>electromagnetic interaction</strong>.<=
/p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Types:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Positive charge (+) =E2=80=94 e.g., proton</p></li>
<li>
<p>Negative charge (=E2=88=92) =E2=80=94 e.g., electron</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Unit:</strong> Coulomb (C)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Law of conservation:</strong> Charge can neither be created nor =
destroyed; it can only be transferred.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=E2=9A=A12.Coulomb=E2=80=99sLaw">=E2=9A=A1 <str=
ong>2. Coulomb=E2=80=99s Law</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Describes the <strong>force between two electric charges</strong>.<br>
[<br>
F =3D k \frac{q_1 q_2}{r^2}<br>
]<br>
Where:</p></li>
<li>
<p>( F ) =3D force between charges</p></li>
<li>
<p>( q_1, q_2 ) =3D magnitudes of charges</p></li>
<li>
<p>( r ) =3D distance between them</p></li>
<li>
<p>( k =3D \frac{1}{4\pi \varepsilon_0} ) =3D proportionality constant</p><=
/li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=A7=A0 <strong>Key Point:</strong><br>
Force is <strong>attractive</strong> for opposite charges and <strong>repul=
sive</strong> for like charges.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=E2=9A=A13.ElectricField(E)">=E2=9A=A1 <strong>=
3. Electric Field (E)</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> The region around a charged particle where =
it exerts a force on other charges.<br>
[<br>
E =3D \frac{F}{q}<br>
]</p></li>
<li>
<p>Unit: <strong>N/C (Newton per Coulomb)</strong> or <strong>V/m (Volt per=
 meter)</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Direction:</strong> Away from positive, toward negative charge</=
p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=E2=9A=A14.Gauss=E2=80=99sLaw">=E2=9A=A1 <stron=
g>4. Gauss=E2=80=99s Law</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Relates the <strong>electric flux</strong> through a closed surface to t=
he <strong>charge enclosed</strong>.<br>
[<br>
\oint E \cdot dA =3D \frac{Q_{enclosed}}{\varepsilon_0}<br>
]</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=93=98 <strong>Meaning:</strong><br>
The total electric flux through a closed surface is <strong>proportional to=
 the total charge enclosed</strong> by it.</p>
<p>=F0=9F=94=B9 <strong>Used to calculate:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Electric field of <strong>symmetric charge distributions</strong> (spher=
ical, cylindrical, planar).</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=E2=9A=A15.ElectricPotential(V)">=E2=9A=A1 <str=
ong>5. Electric Potential (V)</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Work done in bringing a unit positive charg=
e from infinity to a point in an electric field.<br>
[<br>
V =3D \frac{W}{q}<br>
]</p></li>
<li>
<p>Unit: <strong>Volt (V)</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Relation with electric field:</strong><br>
[<br>
E =3D -\frac{dV}{dx}<br>
]</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=A7=B26.MagneticField(B)">=F0=9F=A7=B2 <s=
trong>6. Magnetic Field (B)</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> The region around a moving charge or magnet=
 where magnetic forces act.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Unit:</strong> Tesla (T)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Right-Hand Rule:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Thumb =E2=86=92 Current direction</p></li>
<li>
<p>Fingers =E2=86=92 Magnetic field direction</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=A7=A0 <strong>Created by:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Moving charges (current-carrying wires)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Permanent magnets</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=A7=B27.Faraday=E2=80=99sLawofElectromagn=
eticInduction">=F0=9F=A7=B2 <strong>7. Faraday=E2=80=99s Law of Electromagn=
etic Induction</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> A changing magnetic field induces an <stron=
g>electromotive force (EMF)</strong> in a conductor.<br>
[<br>
\text{EMF} =3D -\frac{d\Phi_B}{dt}<br>
]<br>
Where ( \Phi_B ) =3D magnetic flux =3D ( B \cdot A )</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=9A=A1 <strong>Key Idea:</strong><br>
Changing magnetic field =E2=86=92 Induced voltage =E2=86=92 Induced current=
</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=8C=908.Maxwell=E2=80=99sEquations">=F0=
=9F=8C=90 <strong>8. Maxwell=E2=80=99s Equations</strong></h2>
<p>These are the <strong>four fundamental laws</strong> that describe all c=
lassical electromagnetism.</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"c51ccc1e-1e51-411a-a5b8-6e2=
626704f60" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Equation</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Name</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Description</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>( \nabla \cdot E =3D \frac{\rho}{\varepsilon_0} )</p></li>
</ol></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Gauss=E2=80=99s Law for Electricity</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Electric field originates from electric charges</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<ol start=3D"2">
<li>
<p>( \nabla \cdot B =3D 0 )</p></li>
</ol></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Gauss=E2=80=99s Law for Magnetism</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>No magnetic monopoles exist</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<ol start=3D"3">
<li>
<p>( \nabla \times E =3D -\frac{\partial B}{\partial t} )</p></li>
</ol></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Faraday=E2=80=99s Law</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Changing magnetic field induces electric field</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<ol start=3D"4">
<li>
<p>( \nabla \times B =3D \mu_0 J + \mu_0 \varepsilon_0 \frac{\partial E}{\p=
artial t} )</p></li>
</ol></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Ampere-Maxwell Law</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Electric current and changing electric field create magnetic field</p></=
td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B99.QuickSummaryTable">=F0=9F=94=B9 <=
strong>9. Quick Summary Table</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"44ca38bd-aa6c-4a0b-96d3-b2b=
6ab87ab24" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Concept</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Definition</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Unit / Formula</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Charge</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Property causing electric force</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Coulomb (C)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Coulomb=E2=80=99s Law</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Force between charges</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( F =3D k q_1 q_2 / r^2 )</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Electric Field</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Force per unit charge</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( E =3D F/q )</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Gauss=E2=80=99s Law</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Electric flux =3D enclosed charge / =CE=B5=E2=82=80</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( \oint E=C2=B7dA =3D Q/=CE=B5=E2=82=80 )</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Electric Potential</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Work done per unit charge</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Volt (V)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Magnetic Field</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Force field due to moving charges</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Tesla (T)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Faraday=E2=80=99s Law</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Induced EMF from changing flux</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( EMF =3D -d=CE=A6/dt )</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Maxwell=E2=80=99s Equations</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Unified electromagnetism laws</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>4 vector equations</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>In Short:</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Electric and magnetic fields are created by <strong>charges and their mo=
tion</strong>.<br><strong>Coulomb=E2=80=99s law</strong> defines force betw=
een charges, <strong>Gauss=E2=80=99s law</strong> links field and charge, <=
strong>Faraday=E2=80=99s law</strong> links changing magnetic fields to ele=
ctric effects, and <strong>Maxwell=E2=80=99s equations</strong> unify all o=
f these into the complete theory of <strong>electromagnetism</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol start=3D"2">
<li>
<p>Waves and oscillations</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Perfect =F0=9F=91=8F =E2=80=94 now let=E2=80=99s clearly explain <strong=
>Waves and Oscillations</strong>, a very common topic in <strong>physics an=
d electronics fundamentals</strong> for IT and engineering exams.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=8C=8A1.WhatareOscillations?">=F0=9F=8C=
=8A <strong>1. What are Oscillations?</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong><br>
Oscillation means a <strong>back-and-forth (repetitive) motion</strong> of =
a body around a <strong>mean or equilibrium position</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Pendulum swinging</p></li>
<li>
<p>Mass attached to a spring</p></li>
<li>
<p>Alternating current (AC) in an electrical circuit</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=A7=A9TypesofOscillations">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <=
strong>Types of Oscillations</strong></h3>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"be36b008-cad9-4c16-966e-830=
b29870477" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Type</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Description</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Example</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Free Oscillation</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Body oscillates naturally without external force</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Pendulum swinging freely</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Forced Oscillation</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>An external periodic force keeps it oscillating</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Sound from loudspeaker</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Damped Oscillation</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Amplitude gradually decreases due to friction/resistance</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Motion of pendulum in air</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Undamped Oscillation</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>No energy loss, amplitude remains constant</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Ideal spring in vacuum</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Resonance</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>When the external frequency =3D natural frequency =E2=86=92 Maximum ampl=
itude</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Tuning fork resonance</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9KeyTerms">=F0=9F=94=B9 <strong>Key =
Terms</strong></h3>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"20660a09-7188-434d-a9fb-20e=
c9a1a652c" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Term</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Meaning</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Formula / Unit</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Amplitude (A)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Maximum displacement from mean position</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>meter (m)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Time Period (T)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Time for one complete oscillation</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>seconds (s)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Frequency (f)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Number of oscillations per second</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( f =3D 1/T ), Hertz (Hz)</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Angular Frequency (=CF=89)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( =CF=89 =3D 2=CF=80f )</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>radians/sec</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Phase (=CF=95)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Describes position of oscillation at any instant</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>radians</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=E2=9A=99=EF=B8=8FSimpleHarmonicMotion(SHM)">=
=E2=9A=99=EF=B8=8F <strong>Simple Harmonic Motion (SHM)</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>The simplest form of oscillation.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Restoring force</strong> is directly proportional to displacemen=
t and opposite in direction.<br>
[<br>
F =3D -kx<br>
]<br>
where ( k ) =3D spring constant, ( x ) =3D displacement</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Equation of SHM:</strong><br>
[<br>
x(t) =3D A \sin(=CF=89t + =CF=95)<br>
]</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Velocity and acceleration:</strong><br>
[<br>
v =3D =CF=89A \cos(=CF=89t + =CF=95)<br>
]<br>
[<br>
a =3D -=CF=89^2A \sin(=CF=89t + =CF=95)<br>
]</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=8C=8A2.WhatareWaves?">=F0=9F=8C=8A <stro=
ng>2. What are Waves?</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong><br>
A <strong>wave</strong> is a <strong>disturbance</strong> that <strong>tran=
sfers energy</strong> from one point to another <strong>without transferrin=
g matter</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=A7=A9TypesofWaves">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>=
Types of Waves</strong></h3>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"c1584142-fc3e-40e1-976d-34f=
ae990e22a" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Type</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Description</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Example</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Mechanical Waves</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Require a medium to travel</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Sound waves, water waves</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Electromagnetic Waves</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Do <strong>not</strong> need a medium</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Light, radio, microwaves</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Transverse Waves</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Particle motion =E2=9F=82 direction of wave</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Light wave, wave on string</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Longitudinal Waves</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Particle motion =E2=88=A5 direction of wave</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Sound wave</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=93=98WaveProperties">=F0=9F=93=98 <stron=
g>Wave Properties</strong></h3>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
