</table>
</div>
<hr>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>In Short:</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Oscillations</strong> are periodic back-and-forth motions, while=
 <strong>waves</strong> are disturbances that transfer energy through space=
.<br>
Together, they explain how <strong>energy, sound, and light</strong> propag=
ate in nature and in electrical/electromagnetic systems.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol start=3D"3">
<li>
<p>Theory of special relativity</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Let=E2=80=99s clearly explain <strong>Theory of Special Relativity</stro=
ng> =E2=80=94 one of the most important topics in modern physics developed =
by <strong>Albert Einstein (1905)</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=E2=9A=A11.Introduction">=E2=9A=A1 <strong>1. I=
ntroduction</strong></h2>
<p>The <strong>Theory of Special Relativity</strong> explains how <strong>s=
pace, time, and motion</strong> are related, especially when objects move <=
strong>at or near the speed of light</strong>.</p>
<p>It <strong>replaced Newton=E2=80=99s classical mechanics</strong> for hi=
gh-speed motion (close to light speed).</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=A7=AD2.BasicIdea">=F0=9F=A7=AD <strong>2=
. Basic Idea</strong></h2>
<p>Einstein proposed that <strong>the laws of physics are the same for all =
observers</strong> moving at constant speed (inertial frames), and that <st=
rong>the speed of light is always constant</strong>, no matter how fast the=
 observer is moving.</p>
<p>This led to revolutionary changes in how we understand <strong>time</str=
ong>, <strong>distance</strong>, <strong>mass</strong>, and <strong>energy<=
/strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=93=983.TwoPostulatesofSpecialRelativity"=
>=F0=9F=93=98 <strong>3. Two Postulates of Special Relativity</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"7e028db8-7320-47c1-9ece-47d=
3ad85d171" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Postulate</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Description</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Principle of Relativity</strong></p></li>
</ol></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>The laws of physics are identical in all inertial frames (i.e., frames m=
oving at constant velocity). There is no =E2=80=9Cabsolute rest=E2=80=9D.</=
p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<ol start=3D"2">
<li>
<p><strong>Constancy of Speed of Light</strong></p></li>
</ol></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>The speed of light in a vacuum, ( c =3D 3 \times 10^8 ) m/s, is the same=
 for all observers, regardless of their motion or the light source=E2=80=99=
s motion.</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=E2=8F=B34.ConsequencesofSpecialRelativity">=E2=
=8F=B3 <strong>4. Consequences of Special Relativity</strong></h2>
<p>Einstein=E2=80=99s postulates led to several surprising results:</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9a)TimeDilation">=F0=9F=94=B9 <stron=
g>a) Time Dilation</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Moving clocks run <strong>slower</strong> compared to stationary ones.</=
p></li>
<li>
<p>Formula:<br>
[<br>
t =3D \frac{t_0}{\sqrt{1 - \frac{v^2}{c^2}}}<br>
]<br>
where:<br>
( t_0 ) =3D proper time (time measured by stationary observer)<br>
( t ) =3D time measured by moving observer<br>
( v ) =3D velocity of moving object<br>
( c ) =3D speed of light</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=95=92 <strong>Example:</strong><br>
Astronauts traveling at very high speeds will age more slowly than people o=
n Earth.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9b)LengthContraction">=F0=9F=94=B9 <=
strong>b) Length Contraction</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Moving objects <strong>appear shorter</strong> in the direction of motio=
n.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Formula:<br>
[<br>
L =3D L_0 \sqrt{1 - \frac{v^2}{c^2}}<br>
]<br>
where:<br>
( L_0 ) =3D proper length (rest length)<br>
( L ) =3D observed length when moving at speed ( v )</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=93=8F <strong>Example:</strong><br>
A spaceship traveling close to light speed will appear shorter to an observ=
er on Earth.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9c)RelativityofSimultaneity">=F0=9F=
=94=B9 <strong>c) Relativity of Simultaneity</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Two events that occur <strong>simultaneously</strong> in one frame of re=
ference may <strong>not be simultaneous</strong> in another frame moving re=
lative to it.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=E2=8C=9B <strong>Meaning:</strong> Time is not absolute =E2=80=94 it de=
pends on the observer=E2=80=99s motion.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9d)Mass-EnergyEquivalence">=F0=9F=94=
=B9 <strong>d) Mass-Energy Equivalence</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Mass and energy are related =E2=80=94 they are <strong>interchangeable</=
strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Formula:<br>
[<br>
E =3D mc^2<br>
]<br>
where:<br>
( E ) =3D energy<br>
( m ) =3D mass<br>
( c ) =3D speed of light</p></li>
</ul>
<p>=F0=9F=92=A5 <strong>Example:</strong><br>
Nuclear reactions convert a small amount of mass into a huge amount of ener=
gy (basis of atomic bombs and nuclear power).</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9e)IncreaseofMasswithVelocity">=F0=
=9F=94=B9 <strong>e) Increase of Mass with Velocity</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>As an object moves faster, its <strong>mass increases</strong> with spee=
d.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Formula:<br>
[<br>
m =3D \frac{m_0}{\sqrt{1 - \frac{v^2}{c^2}}}<br>
]<br>
where ( m_0 ) =3D rest mass.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>This is why <strong>no object with mass can reach the speed of light</st=
rong>, because its mass would become infinite.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=8C=8C5.SpacetimeConcept">=F0=9F=8C=8C <s=
trong>5. Spacetime Concept</strong></h2>
<p>Einstein combined <strong>space and time</strong> into a single 4-dimens=
ional entity called <strong>spacetime</strong>.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Events are described by 4 coordinates: ( (x, y, z, t) ).</p></li>
<li>
<p>Motion and gravity are seen as <strong>curvatures in spacetime</strong> =
(further developed in General Relativity).</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=A7=BE6.ImportantResultsSummary">=F0=9F=
=A7=BE <strong>6. Important Results Summary</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"53884410-2d05-4790-9136-81b=
94e78b2e3" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Concept</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Formula</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Meaning</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Time Dilation</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( t =3D \frac{t_0}{\sqrt{1 - v^2/c^2}} )</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Moving clocks run slower</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Length Contraction</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( L =3D L_0\sqrt{1 - v^2/c^2} )</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Moving lengths shorten</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Mass-Energy Relation</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( E =3D mc^2 )</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Energy and mass are equivalent</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Relativistic Mass</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( m =3D \frac{m_0}{\sqrt{1 - v^2/c^2}} )</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Mass increases with speed</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Speed of Light</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Constant for all observers</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( c =3D 3=C3=9710^8 , m/s )</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=E2=9A=99=EF=B8=8F7.Applications">=E2=9A=99=EF=
=B8=8F <strong>7. Applications</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>GPS systems (account for time dilation)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Particle accelerators (relativistic mass increase)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Nuclear energy (E =3D mc=C2=B2)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Cosmic ray physics</p></li>
<li>
<p>Space-time navigation and astrophysics</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>In Short:</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Einstein=E2=80=99s <strong>Special Relativity</strong> shows that <stron=
g>space and time are not absolute</strong> =E2=80=94 they change with motio=
n.<br>
It revolutionized physics by linking <strong>energy, mass, and motion</stro=
ng> under a single framework and is the foundation of <strong>modern physic=
s and cosmology</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol start=3D"4">
<li>
<p>Electromagnetic waves, Photoelectric effect, Quantum theory of light, X-=
ray and X-ray diffraction, Compton effect</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Let=E2=80=99s go through each of these fundamental physics concepts =E2=
=80=94 they all relate to <strong>light as an electromagnetic wave and as p=
hotons (quantum particles)</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=E2=9A=A11.ElectromagneticWaves">=E2=9A=A1 <str=
ong>1. Electromagnetic Waves</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9Definition">=F0=9F=94=B9 Definition=
</h3>
<p>Electromagnetic (EM) waves are <strong>oscillations of electric and magn=
etic fields</strong> that <strong>travel through space</strong> carrying en=
ergy.</p>
<p>These waves do <strong>not require any medium</strong> =E2=80=94 they ca=
n travel in a <strong>vacuum</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9Properties">=F0=9F=94=B9 Properties=
</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Produced by <strong>accelerating electric charges</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Electric (E)</strong> and <strong>Magnetic (B)</strong> fields a=
re <strong>perpendicular</strong> to each other and to the direction of wav=
e travel.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Transverse waves</strong> =E2=80=94 both fields oscillate at rig=
ht angles to motion.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9Equation">=F0=9F=94=B9 Equation</h3=
>
<p>[<br>
c =3D \lambda \nu<br>
]<br>
where<br>
( c ) =3D speed of light (3=C3=9710=E2=81=B8 m/s)<br>
( \lambda ) =3D wavelength<br>
( \nu ) =3D frequency</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9Spectrum">=F0=9F=94=B9 Spectrum</h3=
>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"128892e5-7ca8-4462-a7f3-5cf=
0224b908b" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Type</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
