<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=E2=98=80=EF=B8=8F2.PhotoelectricEffect">=E2=98=
=80=EF=B8=8F <strong>2. Photoelectric Effect</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9Observation">=F0=9F=94=B9 Observati=
on</h3>
<p>When <strong>light shines on a metal surface</strong>, electrons are <st=
rong>emitted</strong> from the surface.</p>
<p>These electrons are called <strong>photoelectrons</strong>.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9ExperimentalFacts">=F0=9F=94=B9 Exp=
erimental Facts</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>No electrons are emitted below a <strong>certain minimum frequency</stro=
ng> (threshold frequency).</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Intensity</strong> affects the <strong>number</strong> of electr=
ons, not their <strong>energy</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Energy</strong> of emitted electrons depends on <strong>frequenc=
y</strong>, not on intensity.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9Einstein=E2=80=99sExplanation(1905)=
">=F0=9F=94=B9 Einstein=E2=80=99s Explanation (1905)</h3>
<p>Light behaves as <strong>particles (photons)</strong>, each carrying ene=
rgy:<br>
[<br>
E =3D h\nu<br>
]<br>
where ( h =3D 6.626 =C3=97 10^{-34} , J=C2=B7s ) is Planck=E2=80=99s consta=
nt.</p>
<p>If photon energy exceeds the metal=E2=80=99s <strong>work function (=CF=
=95)</strong>, electrons are emitted:<br>
[<br>
h\nu =3D \phi + \frac{1}{2}mv^2<br>
]<br>
=E2=86=92 Kinetic energy of photoelectron =3D ( h\nu - \phi )</p>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>Proved the particle nature of light.</strong></p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=8C=883.QuantumTheoryofLight">=F0=9F=8C=
=88 <strong>3. Quantum Theory of Light</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9DualNatureofLight">=F0=9F=94=B9 Dua=
l Nature of Light</h3>
<p>Light has <strong>both wave and particle properties</strong>:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Wave nature</strong> =E2=86=92 interference, diffraction, polari=
zation</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Particle nature</strong> =E2=86=92 photoelectric effect, Compton=
 effect</p></li>
</ul>
<p>This dual behavior is called <strong>wave=E2=80=93particle duality</stro=
ng>.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9PhotonConcept">=F0=9F=94=B9 Photon =
Concept</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A photon is a <strong>quantum (packet)</strong> of electromagnetic energ=
y.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Energy of each photon:<br>
[<br>
E =3D h\nu<br>
]</p></li>
<li>
<p>Momentum of photon:<br>
[<br>
p =3D \frac{h}{\lambda}<br>
]</p></li>
<li>
<p>Photons have <strong>no rest mass</strong> but carry <strong>energy and =
momentum</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=92=8E4.X-raysandX-rayDiffraction">=F0=9F=
=92=8E <strong>4. X-rays and X-ray Diffraction</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9X-rays">=F0=9F=94=B9 X-rays</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Discovered by <strong>Wilhelm R=C3=B6ntgen (1895)</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Produced when <strong>high-speed electrons</strong> strike a <strong>met=
al target</strong> (like tungsten).</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9Properties.1">=F0=9F=94=B9 Properti=
es</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>High-energy electromagnetic waves.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Can penetrate matter.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Used in medical imaging, crystallography, and material testing.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9X-rayDiffraction(XRD)">=F0=9F=94=B9=
 X-ray Diffraction (XRD)</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>X-rays interacting with <strong>crystals</strong> produce <strong>diffra=
ction patterns</strong> due to regular atomic spacing.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Bragg=E2=80=99s Law:</strong><br>
[<br>
n\lambda =3D 2d \sin\theta<br>
]<br>
where<br>
( n ) =3D order of reflection,<br>
( \lambda ) =3D X-ray wavelength,<br>
( d ) =3D distance between atomic planes,<br>
( \theta ) =3D diffraction angle.</p>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Used to determine <strong>atomic structure</strong> of crystal=
s (e.g., DNA structure discovery).</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=865.ComptonEffect">=F0=9F=94=86 <stro=
ng>5. Compton Effect</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9Discovery">=F0=9F=94=B9 Discovery</=
h3>
<p>Observed by <strong>Arthur Compton (1923)</strong> =E2=80=94 scattering =
of X-rays by electrons results in <strong>change in wavelength</strong>.</p=
>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=94=B9Explanation">=F0=9F=94=B9 Explanati=
on</h3>
<p>When a photon collides with an electron:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>It transfers part of its energy to the electron.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Scattered photon has <strong>lower energy (longer wavelength)</strong>.<=
/p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Formula:</strong><br>
[<br>
\Delta\lambda =3D \lambda' - \lambda =3D \frac{h}{m_e c}(1 - \cos\theta)<br=
>
]<br>
where<br>
( m_e ) =3D electron mass,<br>
( c ) =3D speed of light,<br>
( \theta ) =3D scattering angle.</p>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>Confirmed that light has particle-like momentum.</stro=
ng></p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"id-1_BasicPhysics-=F0=9F=93=98SummaryTable">=F0=9F=93=98 <strong>=
Summary Table</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"74df46ea-c16f-42f2-90a9-d9b=
1e6f5ac0e" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Concept</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Key Idea</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Equation</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Proved</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Electromagnetic Waves</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Oscillating E and B fields</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( c =3D \lambda\nu )</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Maxwell</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Photoelectric Effect</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Photon ejects electrons</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( h\nu =3D \phi + \frac{1}{2}mv^2 )</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Einstein</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Quantum Theory</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Light =3D wave + particle</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( E =3D h\nu ), ( p =3D h/\lambda )</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Planck &amp; Einstein</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>X-ray Diffraction</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>X-rays diffract in crystals</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( n\lambda =3D 2d\sin\theta )</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Bragg</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Compton Effect</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Photon loses energy in scattering</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>( \Delta\lambda =3D \frac{h}{m_ec}(1 - \cos\theta) )</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Compton</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>In Short:</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Light behaves both as a <strong>wave</strong> and a <strong>particle</st=
rong>.<br>
Phenomena like <strong>photoelectric effect</strong>, <strong>Compton scatt=
ering</strong>, and <strong>X-ray diffraction</strong> show its <strong>qua=
ntum nature</strong>, while <strong>electromagnetic wave theory</strong> de=
scribes its <strong>continuous field behavior</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol start=3D"5">
<li>
<p>De Broglie waves, Phase and group velocity, Wave function and wave equat=
ion.</p></li>
</ol>
<p></p>
<p></p>
